# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: language-server-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Autocomplete speeds up human-computer interactions when it correctly predicts the word a user intends to enter after only a few characters have been typed into a text input field.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] It works best in domains with a limited number of possible words (such as in command line interpreters), when some words are much more common (such as when addressing an e-mail), or writing structured and predictable text (as in source code editors).
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Many autocomplete algorithms learn new words after the user has written them a few times, and can suggest alternatives based on the learned habits of the individual user.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] The original purpose of word prediction software was to help people with physical disabilities increase their typing speed, as well as to help them decrease the number of keystrokes needed in order to complete a word or a sentence.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] The need to increase speed is noted by the fact that people who use speech-generating devices generally produce speech at a rate that is less than 10% as fast as people who use oral speech.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] But the function is also very useful for anybody who writes text, particularly people–such as medical doctors–who frequently use long, hard-to-spell terminology that may be technical or medical in nature.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Autocomplete or word completion works so that when the writer writes the first letter or letters of a word, the program predicts one or more possible words as choices.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] If the intended word is included in the list, the writer can select it, for example, by using the number keys.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] If the word that the user wants is not predicted, the writer must enter the next letter of the word.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] At this time, the word choice(s) is altered so that the words provided begin with the same letters as those that have been selected.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] When the word that the user wants appears it is selected, and the word is inserted into the text.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] In another form of word prediction, words most likely to follow the just written one are predicted, based on recent word pairs used.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Word prediction uses language modeling, where within a set vocabulary the words are most likely to occur are calculated.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Along with language modeling, basic word prediction on AAC devices is often coupled with a frecency model, where words the AAC user has used recently and frequently are more likely to be predicted.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Word prediction software often also allows the user to enter their own words into the word prediction dictionaries either directly, or by "learning" words that have been written.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] In the 1950s, typists came to rearrange the character layout from the standard dictionary layout to groups of common words and phrases.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Chinese typewriter engineers innovated mechanisms to access common characters accessible at the fastest speed possible by word prediction, a technique used today in Chinese input methods for computers, and in text messaging in many languages.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] According to Stanford University historian Thomas Mullaney, the development of modern Chinese typewriters from the 1960s to 1970s influenced the development of modern computer word processors and affected the development of computers themselves.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] There are standalone tools that add autocomplete functionality to existing applications.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] These programs monitor user keystrokes and suggest a list of words based on first typed letter(s).
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] LetMeType, freeware, is no longer developed.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] The author has published the source code and allows anybody to continue development.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] TypingAid, also freeware, is actively developed.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] IntelliComplete, available as both freeware and payware, works only in certain programs which hook into the IntelliComplete server program.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] The first autocomplete software was Smartype, which dates back to the late 1980s and is still available today.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] It was initially developed for medical transcriptionists working in WordPerfect for MS/DOS, but it now functions for any application in any Windows or Web-based program.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Autocorrection is a related feature that involves automatic replacement of a particular string with another one, usually one that is longer and harder to type, such as "myname" with "Lee John Nikolai François Al Rahman".
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] This can also quietly fix simple typing errors, such as turning "teh" into "the".
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Several autocomplete programs, standalone or integrated in text editors, based on word lists, also include a shorthand function for often-used phrases.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] In web browsers, autocomplete is done in the address bar (using items from the browser's history) and in text boxes on frequently used pages, such as a search engine's search box.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Autocomplete for web addresses is particularly convenient because the full addresses are often long and difficult to type correctly.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Autocompletion or "autofill" is frequently found in web browsers, used to fill in web forms automatically.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] When a user inputs data into a form and subsequently submits it, the web browser will often save the form's contents by default.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] This feature is commonly used to fill in login credentials.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] However, when a password field is detected, the web browser will typically ask the user for explicit confirmation before saving the password in its password store, often secured with a built-in password manager to allow the use of a "master password" before credentials can be autofilled.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Most of the time, such as in Internet Explorer and Google Toolbar, the entries depend on the form field's name, so as to not enter street names in a last name field or vice versa.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] For this use, proposed names for such form fields, in earlier HTML 5 specifications this RFC is no longer referenced, thus leaving the selection of names up to each browser's implementation.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Certain web browsers such as Opera automatically autofill credit card information and addresses.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] An individual webpage may enable or disable browser autofill by default.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] This is done in HTML with the `autocomplete` attribute in a `<form>` element or its corresponding form elements.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] It has been shown that the autofill feature of modern browsers can be exploited in a phishing attack with the use of hidden form fields, which allows personal information such as the user's phone number to be collected.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] HTML has a `datalist` element that can be used to feed an input element with autocompletions.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] In e-mail programs autocomplete is typically used to fill in the e-mail addresses of the intended recipients.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Generally, there are a small number of frequently-used e-mail addresses, hence it is relatively easy to use autocomplete to select among them.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Like web addresses, e-mail addresses are often long, making typing them completely inconvenient.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] For instance, Microsoft Outlook Express will find addresses based on the name that is used in the address book.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Google's Gmail will find addresses by any string that occurs in the address or stored name.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Autocomplete, often called predictive search, is used to suggest relevant products, categories, or queries as a shopper types into the search bar.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] This feature helps reduce typing effort and guides users toward popular or high-converting search terms.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Many e-commerce systems generate these suggestions dynamically, based on recent search data or trending products, to improve both speed and discoverability.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] In search engines, autocomplete user interface features provide users with suggested queries or results as they type their query in the search box.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] This is also commonly called *autosuggest* or *incremental search*.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] This type of search often relies on matching algorithms that forgive entry errors such as phonetic Soundex algorithms or the language independent Levenshtein algorithm.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] The challenge remains to search large indices or popular query lists in under a few milliseconds so that the user sees results pop up while typing.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Autocomplete can have an adverse effect on individuals and businesses when negative search terms are suggested when a search takes place.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Autocomplete has now become a part of reputation management as companies linked to negative search terms such as scam, complaints and fraud seek to alter the results.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Google in particular have listed some of the aspects that affect how their algorithm works, but this is an area that is open to manipulation.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Autocompletion of source code is also known as **code completion**.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] In a source code editor, autocomplete is greatly simplified by the regular structure of the programming language.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] There are usually only a limited number of words meaningful in the current context or namespace, such as names of variables and functions.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] An example of code completion is Microsoft's IntelliSense design.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] It involves showing a pop-up list of possible completions for the current input prefix to allow the user to choose the right one.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] This is particularly useful in object-oriented programming because often the programmer will not know exactly what members a particular class has.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Therefore, autocomplete then serves as a form of convenient documentation as well as an input method.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Another beneficial feature of autocomplete for source code is that it encourages the programmer to use longer, more descriptive variable names, hence making the source code more readable.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Typing large words which may contain camel case like `numberOfWordsPerParagraph` can be difficult, but autocomplete allows a programmer to complete typing the word using a fraction of the keystrokes.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Autocompletion in database query tools allows the user to autocomplete the table names in an SQL statement and column names of the tables referenced in the SQL statement.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] As text is typed into the editor, the context of the cursor within the SQL statement provides an indication of whether the user needs a table completion or a table column completion.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] The table completion provides a list of tables available in the database server the user is connected to.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] The column completion provides a list of columns for only tables referenced in the SQL statement.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] SQL Server Management Studio provides autocomplete in query tools.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] In many word processing programs, autocompletion decreases the amount of time spent typing repetitive words and phrases.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] The source material for autocompletion is either gathered from the rest of the current document or from a list of common words defined by the user.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Currently Apache OpenOffice, Calligra Suite, KOffice, LibreOffice and Microsoft Office include support for this kind of autocompletion, as do advanced text editors such as Emacs and Vim.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] In a command-line interpreter, such as Unix's sh or bash, or Windows's cmd.exe or PowerShell, or in similar command line interfaces, autocomplete of command names and file names may be accomplished by keeping track of all the possible names of things the user may access.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Here autocomplete is usually done by pressing the Tab ↹ key after typing the first several letters of the word.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] For example, if the only file in the current directory that starts with x is xLongFileName, the user may prefer to type x and autocomplete to the complete name.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] If there were another file name or command starting with x in the same scope, the user would type more letters or press the Tab key repeatedly to select the appropriate text.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Although research has shown that word prediction software does decrease the number of keystrokes needed and improves the written productivity of children with disabilities, there are mixed results as to whether or not word prediction actually increases speed of output.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] It is thought that the reason why word prediction does not always increase the rate of text entry is because of the increased cognitive load and requirement to move eye gaze from the keyboard to the monitor.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] In order to reduce this cognitive load, parameters such as reducing the list to five likely words, and having a vertical layout of those words may be used.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] The vertical layout is meant to keep head and eye movements to a minimum, and also gives additional visual cues because the word length becomes apparent.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Several studies have found that word prediction performance and satisfaction increases when the word list is closer to the keyboard, because of the decreased amount of eye-movements needed.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Software with word prediction is produced by multiple manufacturers.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] The software can be bought as an add-on to common programs such as Microsoft Word (for example, WordQ+SpeakQ, Typing Assistant, Co:Writer, Wivik, Ghotit Dyslexia), or as one of many features on an AAC device (PRC's Pathfinder, Dynavox Systems, Saltillo's ChatPC products).
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Some well known programs: Intellicomplete, which is available in both a freeware and a payware version, but works only with programs which are made to work with it.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] Letmetype and Typingaid are both freeware programs which work in any text editor.
[src:language-server-protocol/autocomplete] An early version of autocompletion was described in 1967 by H.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] An **integrated development environment** (**IDE**) is software that provides a relatively comprehensive set of features for software development.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] An IDE is intended to enhance productivity by providing development features with a consistent user experience as opposed to using separate tools, such as vi, GDB, GCC, and make.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] At a minimum, an IDE typically supports source-code editing, source control, build automation, and debugging.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] An IDE may include support for integrating tools such as a compiler, runtime environment or version control system, but sometimes such tools are bundled with the IDE.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Some IDEs provide special support for constructing a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Many IDEs support object-oriented programming via features such as class browser and object browser.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Typically, an IDE provides special support for one or more programming languages, allowing for features tailored to a language.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Some IDEs can be extended to support additional languages.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Although some IDEs are implemented as an application, some are implemented as a library, often designed for a particular software platform.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] For example, although Eclipse is a platform for which there are many plugins that each provide an IDE experience, the core application does not.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] While modern IDEs are GUI-based, there were IDEs before the availability of windowing systems like Windows and the X Window System.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] For example, Turbo Pascal for MS-DOS has a full-screen, text-based user experience.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] IDEs initially became possible when developing via a console or terminal.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Early systems could not support one, since programs were submitted to a compiler or assembler via punched cards, paper tape, etc.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Dartmouth BASIC was the first language to be created with an IDE (and was also the first to be designed for use while sitting in front of a console or terminal).
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Its IDE (part of the Dartmouth Time-Sharing System) was command-based, and therefore did not look much like the menu-driven, graphical IDEs popular after the advent of the graphical user interface.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] However it integrated editing, file management, compilation, debugging and execution in a manner consistent with a modern IDE.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Maestro I is a product from Softlab Munich and was the world's first integrated development environment for software.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Maestro I was installed for 22,000 programmers worldwide.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Until 1989, 6,000 installations existed in the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Maestro was arguably the world leader in this field during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Today one of the last Maestro I can be found in the Museum of Information Technology at Arlington in Texas.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] One of the first IDEs with a plug-in concept was Softbench.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] In 1995 *Computerwoche* commented that the use of an IDE was not well received by developers since it would fence in their creativity.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] As of August 2023, the most commonly searched for IDEs on Google Search were Visual Studio, Visual Studio Code, and Eclipse.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] , allowing them to be installed on the same IDE at the same time.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Another example is JDoodle, an online cloud-based IDE that supports 88 languages.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] , which are selected between automatically based on file extension, environment or project settings.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] feature usually includes syntax highlighting, it can show both the structures, the language keywords and the syntax errors with visually distinct colors and font effects.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Code syntax can be continuously validated while it is being edited and errors can be provided an error are introduced instead of the developer waiting until a build is run.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] The IDE may support searching for class and function declarations, usages, variable and field read/write, etc.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] The IDE may also support searching for an implementation of a declaration.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] One typical aim of an IDE is to reduce the configuration necessary to integrate multiple development utilities.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] An IDE can provide for a cohesive configuration aspect that reduces setup time and therefore increases productivity, especially in cases where learning to use the IDE is faster than otherwise integrating and learning multiple tools.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Debugging support usually includes setting breakpoints in the editor, visual rendering of steps, etc.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Visual Basic allows users to design an application by moving programming, building blocks, or code nodes to create flowcharts or structure diagrams that are then compiled or interpreted.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] supports flowcode and is a popular open-source IDE and Simulator for developing software for microcontrollers.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] design and has been used to develop real-time music performance software since the 1980s.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] where the end-users want the flexibility of a full programming language, without the traditional learning curve associated with one.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] For a long time and still somewhat today, IDEs are used more commonly in Windows environments than on Unix-like environments.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] IDEs have been popular on classic Mac OS and macOS, dating back to Macintosh Programmer's Workshop, Turbo Pascal, THINK Pascal and THINK C environments of the mid-1980s.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Currently, macOS programmers can choose between native IDEs like Xcode and third-party tools such as Eclipse, Netbeans and ActiveState Komodo.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Instead of using an IDE, developing software for a Unix-like environment often involves using various command-line tools such as the GNU toolchain (including GCC, GDB, and make) and an text editor such as Emacs or Vim.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Some programmers prefer managing makefiles (and similar build files) over the build configuration experience presented by an IDE.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] For example, most contributors to the PostgreSQL database use make and GDB directly.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Even when building PostgreSQL for Windows via Visual C++, Perl scripts are used as a replacement for make rather than relying on any IDE features.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Some Linux IDEs such as Geany attempt to provide a graphical front end to traditional build operations.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Data Display Debugger is graphical front-end for many text-based debugger tools.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] An online integrated development environment, also known as a web IDE or cloud IDE, is a browser based IDE that allows for software development or web development.An online IDE can be accessed from a web browser, allowing for a portable work environment.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] An online IDE does not usually contain all of the same features as a traditional or desktop IDE although all of the basic IDE features, such as syntax highlighting, are typically present.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] A Mobile-Based Integrated Development Environment (IDE) is a software application that provides a comprehensive suite of tools for software development on mobile platforms.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Unlike traditional desktop IDEs, mobile-based IDEs are designed to run on smartphones and tablets, allowing developers to write, debug, and deploy code directly from their mobile devices.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] As AI assistance is increasing in IDEs, the concept of agentic development environment (ADE) began to appear.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Agents not only suggest code completions but explain code, analyze bugs, suggest solutions, plan them and implement them.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Some ADEs are plugins in regular IDEs as GitHub Copilot, Cline and Continue for Visual Studio Code, while some are deeply integrated as Windsurf, Cursor and Google Antigravity.
[src:language-server-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Zed Editor also has optional AI, while the upcoming Jetbrains Fleet Editor was cancelled in favor of an ADE called Jetbrains Air that is based on it.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] The JSON-RPC protocol is transport-independent and can be carried over many different data transport protocols, including file descriptor I/O, HTTP and TCP.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] It does not directly provide any support for authentication or authorization.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] JSON-RPC works by sending a request to a server implementing this protocol.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] The client in that case is typically software intending to call a single method of a remote system.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] Multiple input parameters can be passed to the remote method as an array or object, whereas the method itself can return multiple output data as well.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] All transfer types are single objects, serialized using JSON.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] A request is a call to a specific method provided by a remote system.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] The receiver of the request must reply with a valid response to all received requests.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] A response can contain the members mentioned below.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] Since there are situations where no response is needed or even desired, notifications were introduced.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] A notification is similar to a request except for the id, which is not needed because no response will be returned.
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] In this case the `id` property should be omitted (Version 2.0) or be `null` (Version 1.0).
[src:language-server-protocol/json-rpc] In these examples, `-->` denotes data sent to a service (*request*), while `<--` denotes data coming from a service.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] The goal of the protocol is to allow programming language support to be implemented and distributed independently of any given editor or IDE.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] In the early 2020s, LSP quickly became a "norm" for language intelligence tools providers.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] LSP was originally developed for Microsoft Visual Studio Code and is now an open standard.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] On June 27, 2016, Microsoft announced a collaboration with Red Hat and Codenvy to standardize the protocol's specification.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Its specification is hosted and developed on GitHub.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Modern IDEs provide programmers with sophisticated features like code completion, refactoring, navigating to a symbol's definition, syntax highlighting, and error and warning markers.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] For example, in a text-based programming language, a programmer might want to rename a method `read`.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] The programmer could either manually edit the respective source code files and change the appropriate occurrences of the old method name into the new name, or instead use an IDE's refactoring capabilities to make all the necessary changes automatically.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] To be able to support this style of refactoring, an IDE needs a sophisticated understanding of the programming language that the program's source is written in.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] A programming tool without such an understanding—for example, one that performs a naive search-and-replace instead—could introduce errors.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] When renaming a `read` method, for example, the tool should not replace the partial match in a variable that might be called `readyState`, nor should it replace the portion of a code comment containing the word "already".
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Neither should renaming a local variable `read`, for example, end up altering identically-named variables in other scopes.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Conventional compilers or interpreters for a specific programming language are typically unable to provide these *language services*, because they are written with the goal of either transforming the source code into object code or immediately executing the code.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Additionally, language services must be able to handle source code that is not well-formed, e.g. because the programmer is in the middle of editing and has not yet finished typing a statement, procedure, or other construct.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Additionally, small changes to a source code file which are done during typing usually change the semantics of the program.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] In order to provide instant feedback to the user, the editing tool must be able to very quickly evaluate the syntactical and semantical consequences of a specific modification.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Compilers and interpreters therefore provide a poor candidate for producing the information needed for an editing tool to consume.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Prior to the design and implementation of the Language Server Protocol for the development of Visual Studio Code, most language services were generally tied to a given IDE or other editor.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] In the absence of the Language Server Protocol, language services are typically implemented by using a tool-specific extension API.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Providing the same language service to another editing tool requires effort to adapt the existing code so that the service may target the second editor's extension interfaces.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] The Language Server Protocol allows for decoupling language services from the editor so that the services may be contained within a general-purpose *language server*.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Any editor can inherit sophisticated support for many different languages by making use of existing language servers.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Similarly, a programmer involved with the development of a new programming language can make services for that language available to existing editing tools.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] LSP is not restricted to programming languages.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] It can be used for any kind of text-based language, like specifications or domain-specific languages (DSL).
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] When a user edits one or more source code files using a language server protocol-enabled tool, the tool acts as a *client* that consumes the *language services* provided by a *language server*.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] The tool may be a text editor or IDE and the language services could be refactoring, code completion, etc.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] The client informs the server about what the user is doing, e.g., opening a file or inserting a character at a specific text position.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] The client can also request the server to perform a language service, e.g. to format a specified range in the text document.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] The server answers a client's request with an appropriate response.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] For example, the formatting request is answered either by a response that transfers the formatted text to the client or by an error response containing details about the error.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] The Language Server Protocol defines the messages to be exchanged between client and language server.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] They are JSON-RPC preceded by headers similar to HTTP.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] Messages may originate from the server or client.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] The protocol does not make any provisions about how requests, responses and notifications are transferred between client and server.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] For example, client and server could be components within the same process exchanging JSON strings via method calls.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] They could also be different processes on the same or on different machines communicating via network sockets.
[src:language-server-protocol/language-server-protocol] There are lists of LSP-compatible implementations, maintained by the community-driven Langserver.org or Microsoft.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] A **text editor** is interactive software that allows a user to edit plain text, such as Notepad.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] As source code is text, any text editor can be used to edit code, but a source-code editor is designed with features specifically intended for editing code.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some provide integration with software development tools and provide a debugging environment.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] There are important differences between plain text (created and edited by text editors) and rich text (such as that created by word processors or desktop publishing software).
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Plain text exclusively consists of character representation.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Each character is represented by a fixed-length sequence of one, two, or four bytes, or as a variable-length sequence of one to four bytes, in accordance to specific character encoding conventions, such as ASCII, ISO/IEC 2022, Shift JIS, UTF-8, or UTF-16.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] These conventions define many printable characters, but also non-printing characters that control the flow of the text, such as space, line break, and page break.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Plain text contains no other information about the text itself, not even the character encoding convention employed.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Plain text is stored in text files, although text files do not exclusively store plain text.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Since the early days of computers, plain text was (once by necessity and now by convention) generally displayed using a monospaced font, such that horizontal alignment and columnar formatting were sometimes done using whitespace characters.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Rich text can be saved in binary format (e.g.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] DOC), text files adhering to a markup language (e.g.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] RTF or HTML), or in a hybrid form of both (e.g.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Text editors are intended to open and save text files containing either plain text or anything that can be interpreted as plain text, including the markup for rich text or the markup for something else (e.g.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Before text editors existed, computer text was punched into cards with keypunch machines.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Physical boxes of these thin cardboard cards were then inserted into a card reader.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Magnetic tape, drum and disk card image files created from such card decks often had no line-separation characters at all, and assumed fixed-length 80- or 90-character records.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] An alternative to cards was Punched tape.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] It could be created by some teleprinters (such as the Teletype), which used special characters to indicate ends of records.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some early operating systems included batch text editors, either integrated with language processors or as separate utility programs; one early example was the ability to edit SQUOZE source files for SCAT in the SHARE Operating System.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] The first interactive text editors were "line editors" oriented to teletypes: teleprinter-style or typewriter-style terminals that mechanically printed both input and output on the same continuous roll of paper, without an illuminated display.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Commands (often a single keystroke) effected edits to a file at an insertion point, that the operator needed to keep track of, called the "cursor".
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Edits were verified by typing a command to print a small section of the file, and periodically by printing the entire file.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] In some line editors, the cursor could be moved by commands that specified the line number in the file, text strings (context) for which to search, and eventually regular expressions.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Line editors were major improvements over keypunching.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some line editors could be used by keypunch; editing commands could be taken from a deck of cards and applied to a specified file.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some common line editors supported a "verify" mode in which change commands displayed the altered lines.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] An example configuration, circa 1975, was a Teletype Model 33 as a console to a PDP-11 using Version 6 Unix, manipulating text with the *ed*, the standard UNIX text editor.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] When computer terminals with video screens became available, screen-based text editors (sometimes called just "screen editors") became common.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] One of the earliest full-screen editors was O26, which was written for the operator console of the CDC 6000 series computers in 1967.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Another early full-screen editor was vi.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Written in the 1970s, it is still a standard editor on Unix and Linux operating systems.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Also written in the 1970s was the UCSD Pascal Screen Oriented Editor, which was optimized both for indented source code and general text.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Emacs, one of the first free and open-source software projects, is another early full-screen or real-time editor, one that was ported to many systems.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] The 1977 Commodore PET was the first mass-market computer to feature a full-screen editor.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] A full-screen editor's ease-of-use and speed (compared to the line-based editors) motivated many early purchases of video terminals.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] The core data structure in a text editor is the one that manages the string (sequence of characters) or list of records that represents the current state of the file being edited.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] While the former could be stored in a single long consecutive array of characters, the desire for text editors that could more quickly insert text, delete text, and undo/redo previous edits led to the development of more complicated sequence data structures.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] A typical text editor uses a gap buffer, a linked list of lines (as in PaperClip), a piece table, or a rope, as its sequence data structure.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some text editors are small and simple, while others offer broad and complex functions.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] For example, Unix and Unix-like operating systems have the pico editor (or a variant), but many also include the vi and Emacs editors.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Microsoft Windows systems come with the simple Notepad, though many people—especially programmers—prefer other editors with more features.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Under Apple Macintosh's classic Mac OS there was the native TeachText later replaced by SimpleText in 1994, which was replaced in Mac OS X by TextEdit, which combines features of a text editor with those typical of a word processor such as rulers, margins and multiple font selection.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] These features are not available simultaneously, but must be switched by user command, or through the program automatically determining the file type.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Most word processors can read and write files in plain text format, allowing them to open files saved from text editors.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Saving these files from a word processor, however, requires ensuring the file is written in plain text format, and that any text encoding or BOM settings will not obscure the file for its intended use.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Non-WYSIWYG word processors, such as WordStar, are more easily pressed into service as text editors, and in fact were commonly used as such during the 1980s.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] The default file format of these word processors often resembles a markup language, with the basic format being plain text and visual formatting achieved using non-printing control characters or escape sequences.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Later word processors like Microsoft Word store their files in a binary format and are almost never used to edit plain text files.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some text editors can edit unusually large files such as log files or an entire database placed in a single file.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Simpler text editors may just read files into the computer's main memory.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] With larger files, this may be a slow process, and the entire file may not fit.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some text editors do not let the user start editing until this read-in is complete.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Editing performance also often suffers in nonspecialized editors, with the editor taking seconds or even minutes to respond to keystrokes or navigation commands.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Specialized editors have optimizations such as only storing the visible portion of large files in memory, improving editing performance.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some editors are programmable, meaning, e.g., they can be customized for specific uses.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] With a programmable editor it is easy to automate repetitive tasks or, add new functionality or even implement a new application within the framework of the editor.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] One common motive for customizing is to make a text editor use the commands of another text editor with which the user is more familiar, or to duplicate missing functionality the user has come to depend on.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Software developers often use editor customizations tailored to the programming language or development environment they are working in.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Emacs can even be programmed to emulate Vi, its rival in the traditional editor wars of Unix culture.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] An important group of programmable editors uses REXX as a scripting language.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] These "orthodox editors" contain a "command line" into which commands and macros can be typed and text lines into which line commands and macros can be typed.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Most such editors are derivatives of ISPF/PDF EDIT or of XEDIT, IBM's flagship editor for VM/SP through z/VM.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Among them are THE, KEDIT, X2, Uni-edit, and SEDIT.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] A text editor written or customized for a specific use can determine what the user is editing and assist the user, often by completing programming terms and showing tooltips with relevant documentation.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Many text editors for software developers include source code syntax highlighting and automatic indentation to make programs easier to read and write.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Programming editors often let the user select the name of an include file, function or variable, then jump to its definition.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some also allow for easy navigation back to the original section of code by storing the initial cursor location or by displaying the requested definition in a popup window or temporary buffer.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some editors implement this ability themselves, but often an auxiliary utility like ctags is used to locate the definitions.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Most text editors provide methods to duplicate and move text within the file, or between files.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Cut, copy and paste are often integrated with a system clipboard.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Text editors provide extensive facilities for searching and replacing strings of text, either individually, or groups of files in opened tabs or a selected folder.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] , and listing multiple results in one place.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Often—especially with older text editors—there is only one level of edit history remembered and successively issuing the undo command will only "toggle" the last change.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Modern or more complex editors usually provide a multiple-level history such that issuing the undo command repeatedly will revert the document to successively older edits.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] A separate redo command will cycle the edits "forward" toward the most recent changes.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Ability to jump to a specified line number.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] To define new commands or features as combinations of prior commands or other macros, perhaps with passed parameters, or with nesting of macros.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] To retain options set by the user between editing session.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] With names specified in, e.g., environment, profile, executed automatically at the beginning of an edit session or when opening a new file.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] The ability to display multiple views of the same file, with independent cursor tracking, synchronizing changes among the windows but providing the same facilities as are available for independent files.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] The ability to temporarily exclude sections of the text from view.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] The ability to alter or insert data at a particular column, or to shift data to specific columns.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Reading or merging the contents of another text file into the file currently being edited.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Also, a case-shifting feature could translate to lowercase or uppercase.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some advanced text editors allow the editor to send all or sections of the file being edited to another utility and read the result back into the file in place of the lines being "filtered".
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] and other text that appears in an organized or predictable format.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Editors generally allow users to customize the colors or styles used for each language element.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] after one press navigated to the end of an on-screen row of text.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] typically have dedicated cursor movement keys, as do keyboards on personal computers.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] , have a dedicated field on the screen for entering commands as opposed to text.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Depending on the editor, the user may have to use cursor keys to switch between the command and text fields or the editor may interpret, e.g., specific function keys, as requests to switch.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] (also known as prefix commands or sequence commands) Some editors treat a file as an array of text lines with associated line numbers or sequence numbers, and have a distinct line number field for each text field.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Some editors also support line macros, also known as prefix macros or sequence macros.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] , some editors allow the sequence field to appear after the text field.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Text editors with additional functionality to facilitate the production of source code.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Includes so-called "orthodox editors" that are derivatives of Xedit.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Editors that implement folding without programing-specific features are usually called outliners (see below).
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Folding can be considered a specialized form of outlining.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Designed to manage and streamline large programming projects.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] They are usually only used for programming as they contain many features unnecessary for simple text editing.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] that are assembled by the software controlling the site and do not compose a complete HTML document.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] Allows multiple users to work on the same document simultaneously from remote locations over a network.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] The changes made by individual users are tracked and merged into the document automatically to eliminate the possibility of conflicting edits.
[src:language-server-protocol/text-editor] , are targeted at a single programming language.
